From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] usb: xhci-aeolia: add Baikal settle delays before USB bring-up

The Baikal xHCI controller takes much longer than mainline xHCI expects
to be ready for command-queue traffic after its hosting BPCIe glue is up.
Without an explicit settle window, the first ENABLE_SLOT command issued
by `xhci_alloc_dev` aborts:

  xhci_aeolia 0000:00:14.7: Error while assigning device slot ID:
                            Command Aborted

(observed in `checkpoint/docs/uart-boot-2026-05-08-6x-bpcie-non-fatal.log`
at 14.5s and 26.8s)

This in turn means no USB devices ever enumerate, /dev/sdX never appears,
and the initramfs cannot find the rootfs partition.

Port the timing fix from rmuxnet/ps4-linux-12xx commit f6cf0e0d
("ps4/baikal: USB working motherfuckers"):

- Add `msleep(50)` after the SATA PHY init on Baikal, before the first
  per-controller probe. This matches the ~50 ms gap the working 5.4
  flow had implicitly via the AHCI bring-up.
- Add `msleep(20)` between each successful per-controller probe so the
  internal hub bring-up has time to complete before we touch the next.

Both delays are gated to Baikal via a small `xhci_aeolia_is_baikal`
helper. Aeolia and Belize behaviour is unchanged.

Source for the fix:
  rmuxnet/ps4-linux-12xx, branch ps4-baikal-7.0-port,
  commit f6cf0e0de15d49ca5b54de536dcf6b6865d49a14

Notes for the next iteration:

- rmuxnet's full fix also adds an `xhci_aeolia_setup` retry path that
  re-reads the cap registers and retries `xhci_gen_setup` once after a
  20 ms pause if the caps look bogus on first read. Not included here
  to keep the patch minimal — add only if the msleep(50)/msleep(20)
  pair is not sufficient.
- rmuxnet's separate `xhci_aeolia_init_baikal_sata` helper that splits
  SATA PHY init out of the inline AHCI flow is not picked up either:
  our existing `ahci_init_one()` inline already runs `bpcie_sata_phy_init`
  before this point, so the settle gap lands in the same place
  semantically.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <17146298+meerzulee@users.noreply.github.com>
---
 drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c | 18 ++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 18 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c b/drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c
--- a/drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c
+++ b/drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c
@@ -12,6 +12,7 @@
 #include <linux/slab.h>
 #include <linux/module.h>
 #include <linux/acpi.h>
+#include <linux/delay.h>
 #include <asm/ps4.h>
 #include "xhci-aeolia.h"
 #include "../../ps4/aeolia.h"
@@ -37,6 +38,11 @@
 	.reset = xhci_aeolia_setup,
 };

+static bool xhci_aeolia_is_baikal(struct device *dev)
+{
+	return to_pci_dev(dev)->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BAIKAL_XHCI;
+}
+
 static void xhci_aeolia_quirks(struct device *dev, struct xhci_hcd *xhci)
 {
 	/*
@@ -432,6 +438,15 @@
 		}
 	}

+	/*
+	 * Baikal xHCI needs ~50 ms after SATA PHY init before its command
+	 * queue accepts traffic. Without this, the first ENABLE_SLOT aborts
+	 * with "Command Aborted" and no USB device ever enumerates.
+	 * Source: rmuxnet/ps4-linux-12xx f6cf0e0d.
+	 */
+	if (xhci_aeolia_is_baikal(&dev->dev))
+		msleep(50);
+
 	for (idx = 0; idx < NR_DEVICES; idx++) {
  		if(dev->device != PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_AEOLIA_XHCI && idx == 1){ //this is for Belize and Baikal
 			continue;
@@ -439,6 +454,9 @@
 		retval = xhci_aeolia_probe_one(dev, idx);
 		if (retval)
 			goto remove_hcds;
+		/* Let the internal hub settle before we touch the next host. */
+		if (xhci_aeolia_is_baikal(&dev->dev))
+			msleep(20);
 	}

 	return 0;
